  {"commonName":"Satanic Leaf-tailed Gecko","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"theatrical","typicalLifespanYears":5,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Gekkonidae","genus":"Uroplatus","species":"Uroplatus phantasticus"},"description":"Its name is accurate. Has red eyes and a leaf-shaped tail that makes it disappear against bark. Llamas appreciate the commitment to branding."},
  {"commonName":"Thorny Devil","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"armoured","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Agamidae","genus":"Moloch","species":"Moloch horridus"},"description":"Channels dew from its skin to its mouth through capillary action. Llamas find this technically impressive. The spines are also notable."},
  {"commonName":"Frilled Lizard","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"theatrical","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Agamidae","genus":"Chlamydosaurus","species":"Chlamydosaurus kingii"},"description":"Fans out a large neck frill when threatened, then runs away on two legs. Llamas consider this the correct response to most situations."},
  {"commonName":"Green Iguana","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"imperious","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Iguanidae","genus":"Iguana","species":"Iguana iguana"},"description":"Up to 2 metres long and profoundly unimpressed by everything. One of the most commonly kept large reptiles in the llamaverse."},
  {"commonName":"Blue-tongued Skink","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"calm","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Scincidae","genus":"Tiliqua","species":"Tiliqua scincoides"},"description":"Has a vivid blue tongue it extends slowly when threatened. Llamas find the deliberate drama relatable."},
  {"commonName":"Armadillo Lizard","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"defensive","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Squamata","family":"Cordylidae","genus":"Ouroborus","species":"Ouroborus cataphractus"},"description":"Rolls into a tight ball holding its own tail in its mouth. A living dragon symbol. Llamas who study philosophy keep them."},
  {"commonName":"Mata Mata Turtle","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"eccentric","typicalLifespanYears":75,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Testudines","family":"Chelidae","genus":"Chelus","species":"Chelus fimbriata"},"description":"Looks like a pile of leaves. Waits, motionless, for fish to swim past, then inhales them. Llamas admire its patience and aesthetic choices."},
  {"commonName":"Tuatara","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"ancient","typicalLifespanYears":100,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Reptilia","order":"Rhynchocephalia","family":"Sphenodontidae","genus":"Sphenodon","species":"Sphenodon punctatus"},"description":"The only surviving member of an order that diverged from other reptiles 240 million years ago. Has a third eye on top of its head. Llamas consider it the elder statesperson of the animal kingdom."},

  # ── BIRDS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"commonName":"Barn Owl","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":7,"typicalDisposition":"nocturnal","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Strigiformes","family":"Tytonidae","genus":"Tyto","species":"Tyto alba"},"description":"The most widespread bird species on earth. Silent in flight. Rotates its head 270 degrees. Llamas find it intimidating in the best possible way."},
  {"commonName":"Snowy Owl","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":10,"typicalDisposition":"regal","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Strigiformes","family":"Strigidae","genus":"Bubo","species":"Bubo scandiacus"},"description":"White as fresh snow, yellow-eyed, and profoundly dignified. Llamas in the northern territories keep them as companions and they are worth every scrap of effort involved."},
  {"commonName":"Tawny Frogmouth","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":5,"typicalDisposition":"disguised","typicalLifespanYears":14,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Podargiformes","family":"Podargidae","genus":"Podargus","species":"Podargus strigoides"},"description":"Not an owl. Freezes with its beak pointed up to look like a broken branch. Llamas find its commitment to the bit admirable."},
  {"commonName":"Shoebill Stork","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"ancient","typicalLifespanYears":35,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Pelecaniformes","family":"Balaenicipitidae","genus":"Balaeniceps","species":"Balaeniceps rex"},"description":"Has a beak shaped like a dutch clog. Stares without blinking for hours. Makes a sound like a machine gun when greeting friends. Llamas find it mesmerising."},
  {"commonName":"Harpy Eagle","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":5,"typicalDisposition":"imperious","typicalLifespanYears":35,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Accipitriformes","family":"Accipitridae","genus":"Harpia","species":"Harpia harpyja"},"description":"The most powerful eagle in the world. Talons the size of grizzly bear claws. Llamas who keep them have a special room and a very good falconry licence."},
  {"commonName":"Secretary Bird","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":5,"typicalDisposition":"precise","typicalLifespanYears":19,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Accipitriformes","family":"Sagittariidae","genus":"Sagittarius","species":"Sagittarius serpentarius"},"description":"Stalks across grassland on long legs and stamps on snakes. Looks like it works in administration. Llamas in professional roles keep it as a spirit animal."},
  {"commonName":"Kakapo","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":8,"typicalDisposition":"oblivious","typicalLifespanYears":60,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Psittaciformes","family":"Strigopidae","genus":"Strigops","species":"Strigops habroptilus"},"description":"The world's largest parrot. Flightless. Nocturnal. Booms from hilltops to attract mates. Critically endangered. Llamas consider keeping one a conservation achievement of the highest order."},
  {"commonName":"Magnificent Frigatebird","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":2,"typicalDisposition":"dramatic","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Suliformes","family":"Fregatidae","genus":"Fregata","species":"Fregata magnificens"},"description":"Males inflate a vast red throat pouch to attract females. Has a wingspan of 2.3 metres. Llamas who keep them require substantial outdoor space and a tolerance for theatre."},
  {"commonName":"Resplendent Quetzal","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":7,"typicalDisposition":"elusive","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Trogoniformes","family":"Trogonidae","genus":"Pharomachrus","species":"Pharomachrus mocinno"},"description":"Considered the most beautiful bird in the world by several independent surveys. Its tail feathers are 1 metre long. Dies in captivity unless conditions are perfect. Llamas who succeed are deeply respected."},
  {"commonName":"Lyrebird","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":6,"typicalDisposition":"mimetic","typicalLifespanYears":30,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Passeriformes","family":"Menuridae","genus":"Menura","species":"Menura novaehollandiae"},"description":"Can perfectly mimic any sound it hears, including chain saws, camera shutters, and other llamas. Llamas keep them and are regularly unsettled by the results."},
  {"commonName":"Cassowary","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"dangerous","typicalLifespanYears":40,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Casuariiformes","family":"Casuariidae","genus":"Casuarius","species":"Casuarius casuarius"},"description":"The most dangerous bird in the world. A 5cm dagger claw on each foot. Llamas who keep them do so in a very large enclosure and have signed extensive waivers."},
  {"commonName":"Atlantic Puffin","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":6,"typicalDisposition":"cheerful","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Charadriiformes","family":"Alcidae","genus":"Fratercula","species":"Fratercula arctica"},"description":"A seabird with a vividly painted beak and a dignified waddle. Llamas near the coast keep small colonies. Watching them waddle is considered therapeutic."},
  {"commonName":"Macaroni Penguin","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":5,"typicalDisposition":"rakish","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Sphenisciformes","family":"Spheniscidae","genus":"Eudyptes","species":"Eudyptes chrysolophus"},"description":"Has vivid orange crest feathers. Named after the 18th-century fashion trend. Llamas find the hat-like plumage irresistible."},
  {"commonName":"Hoatzin","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"punk","typicalLifespanYears":15,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Opisthocomiformes","family":"Opisthocomidae","genus":"Opisthocomus","species":"Opisthocomus hoazin"},"description":"Its chicks have claws on their wings like dinosaurs. Smells of manure due to its fermenting crop. Has a punk crest. Llamas who keep them are committed to the full experience."},
  {"commonName":"Bearded Vulture","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"bone-obsessed","typicalLifespanYears":40,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Aves","order":"Accipitriformes","family":"Accipitridae","genus":"Gypaetus","species":"Gypaetus barbatus"},"description":"Its entire diet is bones. Drops them from height onto rocks to crack them. Has orange-red plumage because it bathes in iron-rich mud on purpose. Llamas respect the level of intention."},

  # ── SMALL MAMMALS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"commonName":"Chinchilla","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":10,"typicalDisposition":"erratic","typicalLifespanYears":15,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Rodentia","family":"Chinchillidae","genus":"Chinchilla","species":"Chinchilla lanigera"},"description":"Has the densest fur of any land animal. Jumps unexpectedly to great heights. Llamas find the chaos charming."},
  {"commonName":"Pygmy Slow Loris","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":8,"typicalDisposition":"venomous","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Primates","family":"Lorisidae","genus":"Xanthonycticebus","species":"Xanthonycticebus pygmaeus"},"description":"The only venomous primate. Looks like a soft toy. Llamas who keep them are acutely aware of this contradiction."},
  {"commonName":"Star-nosed Mole","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"sensory","typicalLifespanYears":5,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Eulipotyphla","family":"Talpidae","genus":"Condylura","species":"Condylura cristata"},"description":"22 tentacles around its nose containing 25,000 sensory receptors. Can detect and eat prey in under 120 milliseconds. Llamas find it admirable."},
  {"commonName":"Naked Mole Rat","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"eusocial","typicalLifespanYears":32,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Rodentia","family":"Heterocephalidae","genus":"Heterocephalus","species":"Heterocephalus glaber"},"description":"Cannot feel pain in its skin. Is nearly cold-blooded. Lives in colonies with a queen. Is practically immune to cancer. Llamas study it for longevity tips."},
  {"commonName":"Aye-aye","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":6,"typicalDisposition":"eccentric","typicalLifespanYears":23,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Primates","family":"Daubentoniidae","genus":"Daubentonia","species":"Daubentonia madagascariensis"},"description":"Has a long skeletal middle finger for tapping on wood and extracting grubs. Enormous eyes. Llamas find it fascinating and keep it in tall trees."},
  {"commonName":"Platypus","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":7,"typicalDisposition":"improbable","typicalLifespanYears":17,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Monotremata","family":"Ornithorhynchidae","genus":"Ornithorhynchus","species":"Ornithorhynchus anatinus"},"description":"A venomous, duck-billed, egg-laying, electrosensing, semi-aquatic mammal. When first described to European scientists they assumed it was a hoax. Llamas find this attitude uncharitable."},
  {"commonName":"Pangolin","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"armoured","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Pholidota","family":"Manidae","genus":"Manis","species":"Manis pentadactyla"},"description":"The only mammal entirely covered in scales. Rolls into a ball when threatened. The most illegally trafficked animal in the human world, which llamas find unconscionable."},
  {"commonName":"Capybara","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"serene","typicalLifespanYears":12,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Rodentia","family":"Caviidae","genus":"Hydrochoerus","species":"Hydrochoerus hydrochaeris"},"description":"The world's largest rodent. Universally liked by all other animals. Llamas consider the capybara the embodiment of good social energy. Very popular pets."},
  {"commonName":"Sugar Glider","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":7,"typicalDisposition":"gliding","typicalLifespanYears":15,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Diprotodontia","family":"Petauridae","genus":"Petaurus","species":"Petaurus breviceps"},"description":"A palm-sized marsupial that glides between trees on skin membranes. Llamas who keep them report being occasionally startled by sudden airborne visits."},
  {"commonName":"African Pygmy Hedgehog","sizeClass":"tiny","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"nocturnal","typicalLifespanYears":5,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Eulipotyphla","family":"Erinaceidae","genus":"Atelerix","species":"Atelerix albiventris"},"description":"2000 spines on its back. Anointsitself with new scents by self-licking. Llamas find this habit eccentric but non-judgeable."},
  {"commonName":"Fennec Fox","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":8,"typicalDisposition":"alert","typicalLifespanYears":14,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Canidae","genus":"Vulpes","species":"Vulpes zerda"},"description":"Enormous ears relative to body size, used for heat dissipation and hearing prey underground. Weighs under 1kg. Llamas find it disproportionate in the best possible sense."},
  {"commonName":"Red Panda","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":9,"typicalDisposition":"solitary","typicalLifespanYears":15,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Ailuridae","genus":"Ailurus","species":"Ailurus fulgens"},"description":"Not a bear, not a raccoon. Fluffy. Eats bamboo. Wrist bone acts as a false thumb. Llamas regard it as the peak of casual animal excellence."},
  {"commonName":"Arctic Fox","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":9,"typicalDisposition":"resourceful","typicalLifespanYears":14,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Canidae","genus":"Vulpes","species":"Vulpes lagopus"},"description":"Changes coat from brown to white in winter. The densest fur of any arctic mammal. Llamas in cold regions keep them and the coat synchronisation is considered beautiful."},
  {"commonName":"Meerkat","sizeClass":"small","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"vigilant","typicalLifespanYears":12,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Herpestidae","genus":"Suricata","species":"Suricata suricatta"},"description":"Immune to certain venoms. Takes turns standing guard. Llamas who keep groups of them report a significant improvement in household security awareness."},

  # ── LARGE / GIGANTIC MAMMALS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"commonName":"African Elephant","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"wise","typicalLifespanYears":70,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Proboscidea","family":"Elephantidae","genus":"Loxodonta","species":"Loxodonta africana"},"description":"The largest land animal on earth. Mourns its dead. Has a memory that spans decades. Llamas who keep them require extensive grounds and considerable humility."},
  {"commonName":"Pygmy Elephant","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"gentle","typicalLifespanYears":50,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Proboscidea","family":"Elephantidae","genus":"Elephas","species":"Elephas maximus borneensis"},"description":"A dwarf subspecies of Asian elephant. Rounder face, longer tail, calmer disposition. Llamas consider it the approachable version of a great animal."},
  {"commonName":"Hippopotamus","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"unpredictable","typicalLifespanYears":45,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Hippopotamidae","genus":"Hippopotamus","species":"Hippopotamus amphibius"},"description":"Secretes a natural sunscreen from its skin. Despite appearances, more closely related to whales than to pigs. Llamas keep them in very large ponds and maintain respectful distances."},
  {"commonName":"Pygmy Hippopotamus","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"secretive","typicalLifespanYears":42,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Hippopotamidae","genus":"Choeropsis","species":"Choeropsis liberiensis"},"description":"Half the size of a standard hippo and considerably more manageable. More solitary. Llamas with appropriate space and permits keep them in forest gardens."},
  {"commonName":"Giraffe","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":2,"typicalDisposition":"serene","typicalLifespanYears":25,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Giraffidae","genus":"Giraffa","species":"Giraffa camelopardalis"},"description":"The tallest animal on earth. Its heart weighs 11kg to pump blood up its neck. Llamas who keep giraffes require exceptional ceiling heights and look up to them in every sense."},
  {"commonName":"Okapi","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"shy","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Giraffidae","genus":"Okapia","species":"Okapia johnstoni"},"description":"Looks like a cross between a zebra and a giraffe. Its closest relative is the giraffe. Unknown to science until 1901. Llamas feel a kinship with animals that keep a low profile."},
  {"commonName":"White Rhinoceros","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"stoic","typicalLifespanYears":50,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Perissodactyla","family":"Rhinocerotidae","genus":"Ceratotherium","species":"Ceratotherium simum"},"description":"The second largest land animal. Near-sighted. Surprisingly fast. Its horn is made of keratin — essentially compressed wool. Llamas find this connection profound."},
  {"commonName":"Tapir","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":2,"typicalDisposition":"gentle","typicalLifespanYears":30,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Perissodactyla","family":"Tapiridae","genus":"Tapirus","species":"Tapirus terrestris"},"description":"Has a prehensile snout it uses to grab leaves. An evolutionary holdover from 50 million years ago. Llamas find it endearingly unfashionable."},
  {"commonName":"Clouded Leopard","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":6,"typicalDisposition":"elusive","typicalLifespanYears":17,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Felidae","genus":"Neofelis","species":"Neofelis nebulosa"},"description":"The longest canine teeth relative to body size of any living cat. Can rotate its ankles 180 degrees. Llamas who manage to keep them report the cats' presence as an excellent test of nerve."},
  {"commonName":"Snow Leopard","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":9,"typicalDisposition":"secretive","typicalLifespanYears":21,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Felidae","genus":"Panthera","species":"Panthera uncia"},"description":"Wraps its enormous fluffy tail around itself for warmth in mountain winters. Never roars; only purrs. Llamas in the high Andes sometimes share territory with them."},
  {"commonName":"Wolverine","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":6,"typicalDisposition":"tenacious","typicalLifespanYears":13,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Mustelidae","genus":"Gulo","species":"Gulo gulo"},"description":"Has been documented driving bears off carcasses. Radiates absolute refusal. Llamas who keep them report a subtle improvement in their own personal boundaries."},
  {"commonName":"Sun Bear","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"curious","typicalLifespanYears":30,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Carnivora","family":"Ursidae","genus":"Helarctos","species":"Helarctos malayanus"},"description":"The world's smallest bear. Has a 25cm tongue for extracting honey. Llamas keep them primarily for the facial expressions."},
  {"commonName":"Giant Anteater","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":4,"typicalDisposition":"purposeful","typicalLifespanYears":15,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Pilosa","family":"Myrmecophagidae","genus":"Myrmecophaga","species":"Myrmecophaga tridactyla"},"description":"Eats 35,000 ants and termites per day. Cannot chew anything. Has 4cm claws it folds under when walking. Llamas find its dedication to a single purpose admirable."},
  {"commonName":"Sloth","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":5,"typicalDisposition":"deliberate","typicalLifespanYears":30,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Pilosa","family":"Bradypodidae","genus":"Bradypus","species":"Bradypus tridactylus"},"description":"Moves so slowly that algae grows on its fur. Descends from trees once a week to defecate, a decision llamas consider respectably ritualistic."},
  {"commonName":"Aardvark","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":2,"typicalDisposition":"determined","typicalLifespanYears":23,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Tubulidentata","family":"Orycteropodidae","genus":"Orycteropus","species":"Orycteropus afer"},"description":"The only living member of its order. Has a long sticky tongue. Digs faster than any other animal relative to its size. Alphabetically first in most llamaverse animal encyclopaedias, which it takes no pride in."},

  # ── CETACEANS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"commonName":"Blue Whale","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"immense","typicalLifespanYears":90,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Balaenopteridae","genus":"Balaenoptera","species":"Balaenoptera musculus"},"description":"The largest animal that has ever lived. Its heart is the size of a small car. Llamas who keep them own entire private bays."},
  {"commonName":"Orca","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":2,"typicalDisposition":"strategic","typicalLifespanYears":90,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Delphinidae","genus":"Orcinus","species":"Orcinus orca"},"description":"Has regional dialects. Teaches its young coordinated hunting techniques. Lives in matriarchal family groups. Llamas find the family dynamics familiar."},
  {"commonName":"Sperm Whale","sizeClass":"gigantic","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"deep","typicalLifespanYears":70,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Physeteridae","genus":"Physeter","species":"Physeter macrocephalus"},"description":"Has the largest brain of any animal. Dives 2km deep. Sleeps vertically in groups near the surface. Llamas with access to deep ocean keep them and communicate via interpretive dance."},
  {"commonName":"Beluga Whale","sizeClass":"large","fluffiness":1,"typicalDisposition":"chatty","typicalLifespanYears":70,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Artiodactyla","family":"Monodontidae","genus":"Delphinapterus","species":"Delphinapterus leucas"},"description":"Called the 'canary of the sea' for its wide vocal range. Can change the shape of its forehead bulge (its melon) by moving air. Llamas who keep belugas report highly engaging conversations."},

  # ── PRIMATES ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {"commonName":"Proboscis Monkey","sizeClass":"medium","fluffiness":3,"typicalDisposition":"distinguished","typicalLifespanYears":20,"classification":{"kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","class":"Mammalia","order":"Primates","family":"Cercopithecidae","genus":"Nasalis","species":"Nasalis larvatus"},"description":"Has an enormously elongated nose. Males with larger noses are considered more attractive. Llamas appreciate the straightforward aesthetic criteria."},
